name.text: Domain and Range of a Function

questiontext.text:
Find the domain and range of \(f(x)={@fx@}\).

Give your answer as interval of the real numbers.

Note: To enter intervals of you real line, you should write the relevant text in the table below.

Intervals Input Syntax
\( [a,b] \) cc(a,b)
\( (a,b) \) oo(a,b)
\( [a,b) \) co(a,b)
\( (a,b] \) oc(a,b)
\( (a, \infty) \) oo(a,inf)
\( (-\infty, b] \) oc(-inf,b)
\( (-\infty, \infty) \) oo(-inf,inf)

(a) \(Dom(f)=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

(b) \(Range(f)=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution

(a) To determine the domain of the function, we need to identify any restrictions on the values of \(x\) that would make the expression undefined.

Looking at the function expression \(f(x)={@fx@}\), there are no specific restrictions on the input value \( x \).

The function \( x \mapsto x^2 - {@bb@} \) is a polynomial function, so defined for all real numbers \( x \). Moreover, the absolute value function \( \lvert \cdot \rvert \) is defined for all real numbers.

Therefore, the domain of \(f(x)\) is all real numbers, which can be denoted as,

\( Dom(f) = \mathbb{R} = {@ta1@}\)


(b) Next, we determine the range of the function.
The range represents the set of all possible values that \(f(x)\) can attain as \(x\) varies.

We know that, for all \(x \in \mathbb{R}\)

\(\begin{align} & {@abs(abs(x^2-bb))@} \geq 0 \\ & \Rightarrow {@cc*abs(abs(x^2-bb))@} \geq 0 \\ & \Rightarrow {@cc*abs(abs(x^2-bb))+aa@} \geq {@aa@} \\ \end{align}\)

Hence, for all \(x \in \mathbb{R}\), \(f(x) \geq {@aa@}\), so,

\(Range(f) = \{ y : y \in \mathbb{R}, y \geq {@aa@} \} = {@ta2@} \)

prtcorrect.text: Correct answer, well done.

prtpartiallycorrect.text: Your answer is partially correct.

prtincorrect.text: Incorrect answer.

falsefeedback.text: The absolute value of any real number can be calculated, so there are no restrictions of \(x\) to be considered. Therefore the domain of \(f(x)\) is \(\mathbb{R}\).

We know that \( \forall x \in \mathbb{R}, {@cc*abs(abs(x^2-bb))@} \geq 0\).

We then need to add {@aa@} to the absolute value inequality, making the minimal value of \(f(x)\) to be \({@aa@}\).

Therefore, the Range of the function is \(y \geq {@aa@}\).
